INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '57f8d09a-15b3-4cf5-a11c-5295c92f0e1d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS DI Container — Why Manual Wiring Kills Your Testability$escape$,
  $escape$NestJS's built-in IoC container, powered by `@Injectable()` and module-scoped providers, does more than resolve dependencies — it makes every layer independently mockable. When you register a service via `providers: [UserService]`, the container owns instantiation. In tests, you swap the real implementation with `{ provide: UserService, useValue: mockUserService }` inside `Test.createTestingModule()` — zero refactoring required.

Manual wiring (`new UserService(new PrismaService())`) bypasses the container entirely. Now your controller test must construct the full dependency tree, including transitive deps. Swap one implementation and you're hunting down every `new` call.

Scope matters too. `@Injectable({ scope: Scope.REQUEST })` gives you per-request instances automatically — impossible to replicate cleanly with manual wiring without building your own factory.

The DI token system also enables interface-based injection via `@Inject(USER_REPO_TOKEN)`, letting you bind a concrete class to an abstract contract. This is the pattern that makes swapping Prisma for a test double a one-line change in your module definition.$escape$,
  $escape$// user.module.ts
@Module({
  providers: [
    UserService,
    { provide: USER_REPO_TOKEN, useClass: PrismaUserRepository },
  ],
})
export class UserModule {}

// user.service.spec.ts
const module = await Test.createTestingModule({
  providers: [
    UserService,
    { provide: USER_REPO_TOKEN, useValue: { findById: jest.fn() } },
  ],
}).compile();

const service = module.get(UserService);$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
