INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '43b198cb-90bb-434a-825d-41742bf9f22d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS Project Structure — MVC Modules vs Vertical Slice Feature Folders$escape$,
  $escape$NestJS's module system pushes you toward MVC by default: `UsersModule`, `AuthModule`, `PostsModule` each containing a controller, service, and repository. This works until your codebase scales — then cross-cutting concerns bleed between modules and `UsersService` starts importing `PostsService` importing `UsersService`.

Vertical slice reorganizes by feature capability instead of layer. A `create-user` slice owns its own controller endpoint, command, handler, DTO, and repository query in a single folder. NestJS supports this cleanly: each slice exports a `@Module()` that registers only its own providers, and the root `AppModule` imports slices without knowing their internals.

The practical rule: use MVC modules when a domain entity is shared across many features (`User` is read everywhere). Use vertical slices for bounded workflows (`checkout`, `send-invite`) where cohesion matters more than reuse. NestJS's `forwardRef()` appearing in your module graph is a strong signal to extract that workflow into its own vertical slice. Hybrid architectures are valid — entity modules for shared read models, slice modules for write operations.$escape$,
  $escape$// vertical-slice: feature/send-invite/
@Module({
  imports: [MailModule],
  controllers: [SendInviteController],
  providers: [SendInviteHandler, SendInviteRepository],
})
export class SendInviteModule {}

// root module stays clean
@Module({
  imports: [UsersModule, SendInviteModule, AcceptInviteModule],
})
export class AppModule {}$escape$,
