INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f1986eed-5855-4edf-9a25-cd794b656e46',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS TypeORM — Killing N+1 Queries and Owning Your Migrations$escape$,
  $escape$TypeORM is NestJS's default ORM, but naive usage creates N+1 disasters. When you call `find()` and then access a relation in a loop, TypeORM fires a separate query per entity. Fix it with eager `relations` or — better — an explicit `QueryBuilder` with `leftJoinAndSelect`.

For complex reads, drop down to `QueryBuilder`: it gives you JOIN control, aliasing, and `WHERE` clauses without losing TypeScript safety. For simple CRUD, `Repository` methods are fine — just always specify `relations` upfront.

Migrations: never use `synchronize: true` in production. It auto-alters tables destructively. Instead, run `typeorm migration:generate` to diff your entities against the schema, review the output SQL, then run `typeorm migration:run` in CI. Register `TypeOrmModule.forRoot()` with `migrations: [__dirname + '/migrations/**/*.js']` and `migrationsRun: true` to auto-apply on startup safely.

For query builder vs full ORM: use `Repository` for standard operations, `QueryBuilder` when you need JOINs across 3+ tables or subqueries, and raw `query()` only as a last resort.$escape$,
  $escape$// Fix N+1: use QueryBuilder with explicit JOIN
const posts = await this.postRepository
  .createQueryBuilder('post')
  .leftJoinAndSelect('post.author', 'author')
  .leftJoinAndSelect('post.tags', 'tag')
  .where('post.published = :published', { published: true })
  .orderBy('post.createdAt', 'DESC')
  .take(20)
  .getMany();

// NOT this — fires N+1 queries:
// const posts = await this.postRepository.find();
// posts.map(p => p.author.name); // lazy load = N queries$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
