INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5dddf2e3-255c-4d0d-bfd1-d60169b7c6c3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS Performance — Connection Pooling, Async Handlers, and Response Compression$escape$,
  $escape$NestJS runs on Node.js, so blocking the event loop is your biggest enemy. Three quick wins: connection pooling, truly async handlers, and gzip compression.

With TypeORM or Prisma, configure `pool.max` explicitly — the default is often too conservative for production. TypeORM's `DataSource` accepts `extra: { max: 20 }` for pg's underlying pool. Prisma configures this via the `connection_limit` URL param.

Async handlers are non-negotiable. Every controller method hitting I/O must return a `Promise` or use `async/await`. NestJS doesn't enforce this — a synchronous DB call in a handler will stall the thread. Use `@nestjs/terminus` health checks to surface pool exhaustion early.

For compression, NestJS wraps Express or Fastify. On Express, add `compression` middleware via `app.use(compression())` in `main.ts`. On Fastify (faster by default), register `@fastify/compress`. Fastify's throughput advantage compounds with `compress` — prefer it for high-traffic APIs. Threshold matters: skip compression for payloads under 1KB to avoid CPU overhead.$escape$,
  $escape$// main.ts — Fastify adapter with compression + pool config
import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core';
import { FastifyAdapter, NestFastifyApplication } from '@nestjs/platform-fastify';
import compression from '@fastify/compress';
import { AppModule } from './app.module';

async function bootstrap() {
  const app = await NestFactory.create<NestFastifyApplication>(
    AppModule,
    new FastifyAdapter({ logger: true }),
  );
  await app.register(compression, { threshold: 1024 });
  await app.listen(3000, '0.0.0.0');
}
bootstrap();$escape$,
