INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '507aa6c9-a59d-4e7c-afa2-c79355cc8f52',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS Decorators — Building Custom Metadata-Driven Behavior$escape$,
  $escape$NestJS decorators aren't just syntactic sugar — they're the engine behind Guards, Interceptors, and Pipes. Understanding how to compose your own lets you encode cross-cutting concerns directly onto route handlers.

Use `@SetMetadata()` to attach arbitrary metadata to a handler, then read it inside a Guard via `Reflector`. This pattern powers role-based access control without polluting business logic.

The `@applyDecorators()` utility composes multiple decorators into one, so `@Auth('admin')` can simultaneously attach metadata, apply a `JwtAuthGuard`, and bind a `RolesGuard` — a single decorator doing three jobs cleanly.

Custom parameter decorators via `createParamDecorator()` give you direct access to the `ExecutionContext`, letting you extract deeply nested request data (e.g. a tenant ID from a JWT claim) and inject it as a typed method argument — no manual `req.user` digging inside handlers.

The full decorator chain runs synchronously at class-definition time, so metadata is registered before any request arrives. Reflector reads it at request time — that timing distinction matters when debugging guard behavior.$escape$,
  $escape$import { SetMetadata, applyDecorators, UseGuards } from '@nestjs/common';
import { JwtAuthGuard } from './jwt-auth.guard';
import { RolesGuard } from './roles.guard';

export const ROLES_KEY = 'roles';

export function Auth(...roles: string[]) {
  return applyDecorators(
    SetMetadata(ROLES_KEY, roles),
    UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard),
  );
}

// In RolesGuard:
// const required = this.reflector.getAllAndOverride<string[]>(ROLES_KEY, [
//   context.getHandler(),
//   context.getClass(),
// ]);

@Auth('admin')
@Get('dashboard')
getDashboard() { return this.dashboardService.get(); }$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
